# Boilerplate ctags-style to hex bitmask resolver table
# Think: /etc/hosts for bloom labels; essentially.
# Format: LABEL_NAME MASK
# Masks are 64-bit unsigned integers (hex or decimal).
# Note: Bit 64 is reserved for system use.
#
# As long as the label is a continuous string with normal
# printing characters (UTF-8), any label name should be fine.
#
# They're essentially free-form tags for slots as long as you
# use them strategically, and keep them in-sync between clients.
#
# (Very important to keep clients in sync with this mapping or 
# you bloom the wrong keys without much failure detection)
#
# This can also be hard-coded (even as an enum) in the client.
#

user-label-1  0x1
user-label-2  0x2
user-label-3  0x4
user-label-4  0x8
user-label-5  0x10
user-label-6  0x20
user-label-7  0x40
user-label-8  0x80
user-label-9  0x100
user-label-10 0x200
user-label-11 0x400
user-label-12 0x800
user-label-13 0x1000
user-label-14 0x2000
user-label-15 0x4000
user-label-16 0x8000
user-label-17 0x10000
user-label-18 0x20000
user-label-19 0x40000
user-label-20 0x80000
user-label-21 0x100000
user-label-22 0x200000
user-label-23 0x400000
user-label-24 0x800000
user-label-25 0x1000000
user-label-26 0x2000000
user-label-27 0x4000000
user-label-28 0x8000000
